04807nam a22007575i 9780226690582DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20202020ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2019035396  a97802266905827 a10.7208/97802266905822doi  a(DE-B1597)549363  a(OCoLC)1145590627  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aHV6715b.V39 2020 4aHV6715b.V39 2020 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a364.1/7209732231 aVaz, Matthew, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRunning the Numbers :bRace, Police, and the History of Urban Gambling /cMatthew Vaz. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (208 p.) :b15 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHistorical Studies of Urban America00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- t1 Politics and the Old Policy Wheel -- t2 “Are You Going to Let a Negro Name the Next Mayor of Chicago?”: Investigations and Elections -- t3 This Community Is Being Criminalized -- t4 Half of the Rest of Their Lives in Jail -- t5 We Intend to Run It -- tConclusion: Lottery as an American Way of Life -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEvery day in the United States, people test their luck in numerous lotteries, from state-run games to massive programs like Powerball and Mega Millions. Yet few are aware that the origins of today’s lotteries can be found in an African American gambling economy that flourished in urban communities in the mid-twentieth century. In Running the Numbers, Matthew Vaz reveals how the politics of gambling became enmeshed in disputes over racial justice and police legitimacy. As Vaz highlights, early urban gamblers favored low-stakes games built around combinations of winning numbers. When these games became one of the largest economic engines in nonwhite areas like Harlem and Chicago’s south side, police took notice of the illegal business—and took advantage of new opportunities to benefit from graft and other corrupt practices. Eventually, governments found an unusual solution to the problems of illicit gambling and abusive police tactics: coopting the market through legal state-run lotteries, which could offer larger jackpots than any underground game. By tracing this process and the tensions and conflicts that propelled it, Vaz brilliantly calls attention to the fact that, much like education and housing in twentieth-century America, the gambling economy has also been a form of disputed terrain upon which racial power has been expressed, resisted, and reworked.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aGamblingzUnited States. 0aLotterieszUnited States. 0aUrban African AmericansxGambling. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aChicago.  aFourth Amendment.  aHarlem.  aNew York.  aSouthside.  agambling.  alotteries.  anumbers game.  apolice corruption.  aurban politics.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2020 Englishz978311070473008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2020z9783110704525oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUChP Frontlist eBook-Package 2020z978311069309640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226690582423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226690582.jpg  a978-3-11-069309-6  UChP Frontlist eBook-Package 2020b2020  a978-3-11-070471-6  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishb2020  a978-3-11-070473-0  EBOOK PACKAGE History 2020 Englishb2020  aGBV